46:59.269 --> 47:01.974
<i>If you want to reach the top
you're gonna have to do it.</i>

47:01.975 --> 47:04.845
Everybody thinks anabolic
steroids is the easy way out.

47:04.846 --> 47:07.149
<i>The people that train
with anabolic steroids</i>

47:07.150 --> 47:08.987
<i>train way harder
than people that don't.</i>

47:08.988 --> 47:10.956
<i>Regardless of what people
think of Barry Bonds,</i>

47:10.957 --> 47:13.027
<i>you can't take
a bottle of testosterone,</i>

47:13.028 --> 47:14.663
<i>put on Barry's
baseball uniform</i>

47:14.664 --> 47:16.900
<i>and make him hit
700 home runs.</i>

47:16.901 --> 47:19.806
<i>Barry's got to go out, train
and hit the 700 home runs.</i>

47:19.807 --> 47:21.809
But what if
the scientists came up

47:21.810 --> 47:23.980
with something better
than anabolic steroids?

47:23.981 --> 47:26.818
<i>You see cows, you see
immense, powerful cows,</i>

47:26.819 --> 47:29.557
<i>And they basically have
changed their genes.</i>

47:29.558 --> 47:32.562
<i>If they can change your
genes, would that be illegal?</i>

47:32.563 --> 47:35.267
What would they do then?
Just ban sports in general?

47:35.268 --> 47:37.271
Oh My Lord.

47:40.679 --> 47:44.284
When people see these,
is the first question

47:44.285 --> 47:46.288
<i>"how many hormones
do you pump into them?"</i>

47:46.289 --> 47:48.091
<i>Well, it's two comments.
One would be,</i>

47:48.092 --> 47:50.662
"oh my gosh, what did you
do to that thing?"

47:50.663 --> 47:52.833
And secondly, "it looks
like Arnold Schwarzenegger."

47:52.834 --> 47:54.837
<i>This is a
Belgian Blue Bull--</i>

47:57.409 --> 48:01.482
<i>2600 lbs, all muscle,
all natural.</i>

48:01.483 --> 48:03.986
So tell me again,
you're all natural?

48:03.987 --> 48:05.957
You're not
taking anything?

48:08.830 --> 48:10.799
<i>I think you're ready
for Congress.</i>

48:10.800 --> 48:12.670
<i>He has
a genetic mutation</i>

48:12.671 --> 48:14.940
<i>that allows him to grow
double muscle.</i>

48:14.941 --> 48:16.710
<i>And scientists
have figured out</i>

48:16.711 --> 48:19.014
<i>how to genetically alter
humans the same way.</i>

48:19.015 --> 48:21.352
<i>Dr. Lee Sweeney is
using this technology</i>

48:21.353 --> 48:23.222
<i>to try to cure
muscular dystrophy.</i>

48:23.223 --> 48:25.693
It's obviously going to become
more and more evident

48:25.694 --> 48:27.697
that what we call talent

48:27.698 --> 48:30.435
<i>is really
genetic variation.</i>

48:30.436 --> 48:32.906
<i>There's genetic enhancement
available that might be able</i>

48:32.907 --> 48:35.712
to give you what
nature didn't give you.

48:35.713 --> 48:39.218
<i>Trying to figure out how
to do it in the safest way</i>

48:39.219 --> 48:41.255
<i>Is something that
hasn't been worked out.</i>

48:41.256 --> 48:43.259
<i>If you find out
that it's safe,</i>

48:43.260 --> 48:45.496
<i>would you be somebody
who would say, "hey--"?</i>

48:45.497 --> 48:46.832
Yeah, I would be
first in line.

48:46.833 --> 48:48.334
'Cause it seems
like this is

48:48.335 --> 48:51.140
<i>the future of sports--
gene doping.</i>

48:51.141 --> 48:53.177
Gene doping, yeah.
I wouldn't do it.

48:54.547 --> 48:57.285
<i>Will gene doping ruin
sports in America?</i>

48:57.286 --> 48:59.088
I don't think so.
I mean, I think

48:59.089 --> 49:01.092
<i>any time there's
a new technology</i>

49:01.093 --> 49:03.729
<i>everyone says, "okay,
we have to stand back</i>

49:03.730 --> 49:06.635
<i>and think about what this is
really gonna mean to society."</i>

49:06.636 --> 49:08.305
And I think
that's the debate

49:08.306 --> 49:10.209
we will come to
in the coming decades.

49:10.210 --> 49:13.180
<i>Good sportsmanship--
you know what that means?</i>

49:13.181 --> 49:15.551
<i>Play fair.</i>

49:15.552 --> 49:17.856
<i>When I was a kid
cheating was pretty clear-cut,</i>

49:17.857 --> 49:20.427
<i>like when the million dollar
man hired the referee's</i>

49:20.428 --> 49:22.564
<i>evil twin brother to cheat
the Hulkster out of his title.</i>

49:22.565 --> 49:24.869
<i>Is that Dave
Hebner or is that Dave Hebner?</i>

49:24.870 --> 49:27.870
You know, cheating in other sports
wasn't all that different.

49:28.371 --> 49:29.371
Remember when Joe Necro

49:28.367 --> 49:31.572
<i>was hot-scuffing the ball
with an emery board?</i>

49:31.573 --> 49:33.408
<i>Something
came out of his pocket.</i>

49:33.409 --> 49:35.813
<i>Chris: And what about when the
Patriots were playing the Dolphins</i>

49:35.814 --> 49:38.050
<i>And they hired
an ex-con to clear</i>

49:38.051 --> 49:40.088
<i>a spot in the snow for
the field-goal kicker?</i>

49:40.089 --> 49:42.125
<i>You can't do that.</i>

49:42.126 --> 49:43.861
I think it's
the most unfair thing

49:43.862 --> 49:45.430
that I've ever been
associated in.

49:45.431 --> 49:48.236
<i>Or like when Rosie
Ruiz won the Boston Marathon.</i>

49:48.237 --> 49:51.408
The mystery woman winner. We
missed her at all our checkpoints.

49:51.409 --> 49:54.414
<i>Why take steroids
when you can take a bus?</i>

49:54.415 --> 49:56.083
<i>And who can forget
when Tonya Harding</i>

49:56.084 --> 49:59.590
<i>hired a goon to take out
Nancy Kerrigan's knee?</i>

49:59.591 --> 50:01.594
Why? Why?

50:01.595 --> 50:03.731
<i>I guess if you can't
beat 'em,</i>

50:03.732 --> 50:05.701
<i>beat 'em
with a lead pipe.</i>

50:05.702 --> 50:08.540
<i>But somehow steroids
seem kind of different.</i>

50:08.541 --> 50:11.111
I thought in undergraduate
school and in college

50:11.112 --> 50:12.747
I was a pretty good
athlete.

50:12.748 --> 50:15.520
But I find
myself angry,

50:15.521 --> 50:18.425
angry in my gut

50:18.426 --> 50:22.065
because these are the same guys
that would have taken me out,

50:22.066 --> 50:24.469
taken me out
not because they had

50:24.470 --> 50:27.341
more god-given
natural talent than me

50:27.342 --> 50:31.249
but because they enhanced
with artificial means.

50:31.250 --> 50:33.786
<i>If using
steroids is cheating,</i>

50:33.787 --> 50:36.691
<i>seems like a whole bunch of other
stuff should be cheating too.</i>

50:36.692 --> 50:39.831
<i>Take Tiger Woods, for example.
He had Lasik eye surgery</i>

50:39.832 --> 50:43.204
<i>and now his vision is 20/15.
That's better than perfect.</i>

50:43.205 --> 50:45.808
<i>My eyes are stable.
My game's a lot better.</i>

50:45.809 --> 50:47.646
I felt pretty good
coming in.

50:47.647 --> 50:49.815
<i>In a game that relies
so much on depth perception,</i>

50:49.816 --> 50:53.455
<i>wouldn't superhuman vision
be a performance enhancement?</i>

50:53.456 --> 50:55.226
<i>Then there's
cortisone shots.</i>

50:55.227 --> 50:57.497
<i>They helped Curt Schilling
win the World Series.</i>

50:57.498 --> 50:59.533
<i>And those are
steroids too.</i>

50:59.534 --> 51:03.574
<i>Truth is, corticosteroids can have worse
side effects than anabolic steroids,</i>

51:03.575 --> 51:05.912
but they're used
in sports every day.

51:05.913 --> 51:07.815
He had a 20-minute
cortisone shot

51:07.816 --> 51:10.421
after Monday's match after
his back tightened up.

51:10.422 --> 51:12.357
<i>Here's an even
more confusing example--</i>

51:12.358 --> 51:14.027
<i>Floyd Landis claims</i>

51:14.028 --> 51:16.197
<i>that he did not take steroids
to win the Tour De France.</i>

51:16.198 --> 51:18.435
<i>Truth is, I
didn't use testosterone</i>

51:18.436 --> 51:20.272
like I'm accused of doing.
I didn't cheat.

51:20.273 --> 51:22.476
I didn't do anything
outside of the rules.

51:22.477 --> 51:25.849
I won the Tour clean
and I deserved to win.

51:25.850 --> 51:27.418
I'm proud of it
and I always will be.

51:27.419 --> 51:30.523
<i>But he did sleep in
his own altitude chamber.</i>

51:30.524 --> 51:32.527
I got my
altitude chamber

51:32.528 --> 51:34.632
out by the garage
these days.

51:34.633 --> 51:37.003
So you made this?

51:37.004 --> 51:38.905
Yeah, it's not actually
that hard to make.

51:38.907 --> 51:41.478
I didn't make the pipe. I got the
pipe from some construction site.

51:41.479 --> 51:43.014
They were putting in
a water main.

51:43.015 --> 51:44.650
Is the result
pretty good?

51:44.651 --> 51:45.985
For me it makes
a difference, yeah.

51:45.986 --> 51:48.023
And how long do you
stay in here for?

51:48.024 --> 51:50.828
Just sleep in there all night.
I don't know, six or seven hours.

51:50.829 --> 51:52.831
Is your wife like,
"what are you doing?"

51:52.832 --> 51:54.835
"I'm gonna sleep
in the chamber."

51:54.836 --> 51:56.305
She hates it.

51:56.306 --> 51:57.974
So you just climb
in there?

51:57.975 --> 51:59.511
Yeah, you want
to try it out?

51:59.512 --> 52:01.748
You won't have a monitor
in there, but I have it set

52:01.749 --> 52:03.051
to, like,
about 13,000'.

52:06.057 --> 52:08.360
<i>See, sleeping
in an altitude chamber</i>

52:08.361 --> 52:10.364
<i>produces a lot more
red blood cells,</i>

52:10.365 --> 52:12.368
<i>which means more oxygen
in your system,</i>

52:12.369 --> 52:15.807
<i>which means more endurance for a
cyclist or a long-distance runner.</i>

52:15.808 --> 52:18.679
<i>There are four ways to increase
your red blood cell count.</i>

52:18.680 --> 52:22.019
<i>You can sleep in an
altitude chamber like Floyd</i>

52:22.020 --> 52:24.757
<i>or you can just train at the
U.S. Olympic training center</i>

52:24.758 --> 52:26.794
<i>at 6,000'
in Colorado.</i>

52:26.795 --> 52:28.664
<i>Then there's
blood doping.</i>

52:28.665 --> 52:31.202
<i>That's when you draw your own
blood a month before the big race,</i>

52:31.203 --> 52:33.339
<i>then re-inject it
the night before.</i>

52:33.340 --> 52:35.744
<i>Finally, there's a drug
called E.P.O.</i>

52:35.745 --> 52:37.614
<i>which simply
tells your body</i>

52:37.615 --> 52:39.484
<i>to produce more
red blood cells.</i>

52:39.485 --> 52:41.821
<i>So that's four ways to
do the exact same thing,</i>

52:41.822 --> 52:45.495
<i>but two are allowed
and two are cheating.</i>

52:45.496 --> 52:47.766
You done yet?

52:51.273 --> 52:54.245
Hey.
That's kind of weird.

52:54.246 --> 52:56.816
No, it's nice, man. Once you get used
to it it's nice sleeping in there.

52:56.817 --> 52:58.920
<i>What's heartbreaking
is my eight-year-old--</i>

52:58.921 --> 53:00.856
<i>his two favorite athletes are
Barry Bonds and Lance Armstrong.</i>

53:00.857 --> 53:03.227
My four-year-old is obsessed
with Floyd Landis.

53:03.228 --> 53:05.365
<i>So what do you tell these kids?
I talk to people all the time</i>

53:05.366 --> 53:07.335
<i>That they go, "who can
my kids believe in?"</i>

53:07.336 --> 53:09.505
And I want to tell them
is "nobody."

53:09.506 --> 53:11.743
I ask not to be judged
and much less

53:11.744 --> 53:13.680
to be sentenced
by anyone.

53:13.681 --> 53:16.853
<i>You can't trust anybody now because
the testing is so ineffective.</i>

53:16.854 --> 53:19.257
You don't know who's really
clean, who's really dirty.

53:19.258 --> 53:22.196
<i>Were you taking any
sort of drugs for that race?</i>

53:22.197 --> 53:24.200
Not what they
fined me with, no.

53:24.201 --> 53:26.270
<i>- But you were taking other stuff.
- Other stuff, yeah.</i>

53:26.271 --> 53:27.940
<i>But isn't that
still cheating?</i>

53:27.941 --> 53:30.644
Still cheating, yeah,
like everybody else.

53:30.645 --> 53:32.315
<i>So that's how
you justify it--</i>

53:32.316 --> 53:33.917
<i>- Everybody's cheating?
- Yes.</i>

53:33.918 --> 53:35.821
When I interviewed Ben
Johnson he basically said,

53:35.822 --> 53:37.524
"look, everybody was
on something."

53:37.525 --> 53:41.966
Well, you know, Ben--
and bless his heart,

53:41.967 --> 53:44.035
he's got to say
everyone was on something.

53:44.036 --> 53:47.041
That's justifying
his own means.

53:47.042 --> 53:48.644
So he has a problem
with you beating--

53:48.645 --> 53:50.314
he has a problem--
he has a problem

53:50.315 --> 53:52.752
- of, you know, me beating him.
- Yeah.

53:52.753 --> 53:54.755
When we were taking
that victory stand,

53:54.756 --> 53:56.859
we were on the stand
and he got the gold medal,

53:56.860 --> 53:59.164
<i>he didn't smile.
He never smiled.</i>

53:59.165 --> 54:00.901
<i>He never celebrated.
And the thing is,</i>

54:00.902 --> 54:04.139
he couldn't really inside share
in the joy of winning. He cheated.

54:04.140 --> 54:06.143
You cheat.
Everybody cheats.

54:06.144 --> 54:07.813
Nobody in this world
is perfect.

54:07.814 --> 54:09.483
Nobody in this life
is perfect-- nobody.

54:09.484 --> 54:13.090
They know that in 1988
six Americans at least

54:13.091 --> 54:15.094
tested positive in Seoul.
And they all shut up

54:15.095 --> 54:17.531
<i>because the biggest money
comes from America.</i>

54:17.532 --> 54:19.534
So who's gonna
get shafted,

54:19.535 --> 54:21.538
Americans
or Ben Johnson?

54:21.539 --> 54:24.510
<i>I think that Ben
Johnson was unfairly singled out.</i>

54:24.511 --> 54:27.382
<i>I think that there's
always scapegoats.</i>

54:27.383 --> 54:30.655
<i>Is there a lot of drug use
going on in Olympics?</i>

54:30.656 --> 54:33.794
Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.

54:33.795 --> 54:36.398
<i>Dr. Exum was the
Director of Anti-Doping</i>

54:36.399 --> 54:38.603
<i>at the U.S. Olympic Committee
for 10 years.</i>

54:38.604 --> 54:41.308
<i>He thought his job was
to stop drugs in sports,</i>

54:41.309 --> 54:43.813
<i>but his bosses had
other priorities.</i>

54:43.814 --> 54:46.551
<i>He told me that over
2000 American athletes</i>

54:46.552 --> 54:49.122
<i>failed their drug tests,
including Carl Lewis,</i>

54:49.123 --> 54:50.959
<i>and they were
covered up.</i>

54:50.960 --> 54:53.029
<i>Nobody believes Carl Lewis
ever failed a drug test.</i>

54:53.030 --> 54:54.866
<i>- Do you have any proof?
- Oh, certainly.</i>

54:54.867 --> 54:58.439
We have just boxes of proof
for everything that I say.

54:58.440 --> 55:00.443
There it is,
book three.

55:00.444 --> 55:03.649
Here's a letter from
then Executive Director

55:03.650 --> 55:06.388
<i>Baaron Pittenger
to Mr. Lewis.</i>

55:06.389 --> 55:09.426
<i>"I must confirm that the
analysis for your specimen 'B'</i>

55:09.427 --> 55:12.332
<i>was positive for
pseudoephedrine, ephedrine,</i>

55:12.333 --> 55:14.770
And phenylpropanolee--
lamine--

55:14.771 --> 55:16.873
- Is that what is is?
- Phenylpropanolamine, yeah.

55:16.874 --> 55:18.643
<i>--IOC banned stimulants.</i>

55:18.644 --> 55:21.648
<i>By policy of the U.S.O.C.,
this finding is cause</i>

55:21.649 --> 55:24.019
<i>for disqualification
from the Olympic team</i>

55:24.020 --> 55:27.125
<i>to the 1988 Summer Olympic
Games in Seoul, Korea."</i>

55:27.126 --> 55:29.563
<i>Wow.</i>

55:29.564 --> 55:31.467
This is basically
a letter that said

55:31.468 --> 55:32.903
that you had failed
the test

55:32.904 --> 55:35.708
and that there was a
consequence to that failure.

55:35.709 --> 55:38.881
As we all know,
that didn't come about.

55:38.882 --> 55:41.485
You actually received
a letter, or a call--

55:41.486 --> 55:43.489
- Yes. - --that you had
failed the drug test--

55:43.490 --> 55:45.592
- Right. - --because
of some stimulants?

55:45.593 --> 55:46.896
Yeah, it was like

55:46.897 --> 55:48.999
a cold medicine type thing,
the herbal supplement.

55:49.000 --> 55:51.603
They made up this term. It
was called "inadvertent use"--

55:51.604 --> 55:54.843
<i>an athlete took something
without meaning to take it</i>

55:54.844 --> 55:58.316
or without meaning to gain
an advantage from taking it.

55:58.317 --> 56:00.353
<i>Mm-hmm.
And so they made that up</i>

56:00.354 --> 56:02.190
<i>to basically kind of
let people off the hook?</i>

56:02.191 --> 56:04.160
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.

56:04.161 --> 56:07.065
Carl's story is--
it's been a cold medicine;

56:07.066 --> 56:09.571
<i>it's been a tea; it's been
some kind of a nutrient.</i>

56:09.572 --> 56:12.075
<i>- It's a stimulant. - CHRIS: So
you're saying these athletes--</i>

56:12.076 --> 56:14.513
<i>- they know what's on the banned substance list?
- They totally know.</i>

56:14.514 --> 56:16.851
They are bombarded with
the banned substance list.

56:16.852 --> 56:18.854
A lot of people say
you failed the drug test,

56:18.855 --> 56:20.858
you raced against
Ben Johnson,

56:20.859 --> 56:24.331
and that maybe--
maybe the gold medal

56:24.332 --> 56:26.335
- should go to the guy next on the stand.
- I understand.

56:26.336 --> 56:29.240
There are a lot of people that are
going to go to their graves saying,

56:29.241 --> 56:31.344
"I know he did it." and you
know what? To hell with them.

56:34.016 --> 56:36.753
<i>You really cannot
fault the athlete for doing that.</i>

56:36.754 --> 56:40.293
You can't fault Carl
when Carl's belief is

56:40.294 --> 56:43.432
that the system sets some rules
and that you need to follow them.

56:43.433 --> 56:45.436
<i>And they made an
exception in his case.</i>

56:45.437 --> 56:48.575
<i>They made an exception in
a lot of people's cases.</i>

56:48.576 --> 56:50.746
<i>But it's the system</i>

56:50.747 --> 56:53.384
<i>that actually teaches
athletes to think that way.</i>

56:53.385 --> 56:55.388
<i>You know, for me</i>

56:55.389 --> 56:57.725
<i>the whole "level playing
field" was a myth.</i>

56:57.726 --> 57:01.065
If we could not do anything
to take doping out of sports

57:01.066 --> 57:04.505
then doping was
meant to be in sports.

57:04.506 --> 57:08.211
The first all-drug Olympics
opened today in Bogota, Colombia.

57:08.212 --> 57:11.150
Athletes are allowed to
take any substance whatsoever

57:11.151 --> 57:13.721
before, after, and even
during the competition.

57:17.429 --> 57:19.732
Oh! He's pulled
his arms off!

57:19.733 --> 57:22.638
He's pulled his arms off. That's got
to be disappointing to the big Russian.

57:26.212 --> 57:28.215
Yeah!

57:28.216 --> 57:31.387
What has made
every major sport

57:31.388 --> 57:33.324
<i>a multi-billion-dollar
entity?</i>

57:33.325 --> 57:35.729
<i>Well, after you
distill it all down,</i>

57:35.730 --> 57:37.298
<i>it's the desire
of the customer,</i>

57:37.299 --> 57:40.537
<i>the fans that fill
these seats and others,</i>

57:40.538 --> 57:44.111
<i>to see bigger-than-life people
doing bigger-than-life things.</i>

57:44.112 --> 57:46.749
<i>What do you think about
athletes using steroids in sports?</i>

57:46.750 --> 57:48.920
Steroids?
I love it if they're on my team.

57:48.921 --> 57:51.157
I think it's totally wrong,
totally wrong.

57:51.158 --> 57:52.793
<i>- Worst offense. Throw them out.
- It's cheating?</i>

57:52.794 --> 57:54.664
Hell yeah, it's cheating.
Are you kidding me?

57:56.601 --> 57:59.205
Oh!

58:01.611 --> 58:03.446
<i>It all gets back to money.</i>

58:03.447 --> 58:05.216
<i>As long as people
continue to buy</i>

58:05.217 --> 58:08.255
Mark McGuire shirts,
Barry Bonds hats,

58:08.256 --> 58:10.659
<i>we're feeding
that monster.</i>

58:10.660 --> 58:13.164
You vote for the Raiders
by wearing the Raiders hat.

58:13.165 --> 58:14.934
<i>You cast your vote for
Nike with your T-shirt.</i>

58:14.935 --> 58:17.505
You know, every day when you
pick a dollar out of your pocket

58:17.506 --> 58:19.676
you're voting.
And if you don't like

58:19.677 --> 58:23.015
athletes juicing up, then
don't vote to have that done.

58:23.016 --> 58:25.186
Don't buy their stuff.
Don't go to the game.

58:25.187 --> 58:27.190
Do steroids.
Become governor.

58:27.191 --> 58:29.361
Be big and strong,
no girly man.

58:29.362 --> 58:31.732
- The Giants, baby!
- Whoo!

58:31.733 --> 58:34.269
Shockey!

58:34.270 --> 58:36.006
Whoo!

58:36.007 --> 58:37.776
<i>Since the
steroid scandals broke</i>

58:37.777 --> 58:39.847
<i>sports revenue has gone
